    <item>
      <title>chown example: recursive update</title>
      <link>http://tracking.feedpress.it/link/15217/12882834</link>
      <comments>https://www.unixtutorial.org/chown-example-recursive-update#disqus_thread</comments>
      <pubDate>Tue, 08 Oct 2019 22:12:07 +0000</pubDate>
      <dc:creator><![CDATA[Gleb Reys]]></dc:creator>
      <category><![CDATA[Basic stuff]]></category>
      <category><![CDATA[chown]]></category>
      <guid isPermaLink="false">https://www.unixtutorial.org/?p=3480</guid>
      <description><![CDATA[chown is a basic Unix command, super useful and very powerful. I have provided a chown example earlier, but would like to show another common way it's used.]]></description>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[
<figure class="wp-block-image"><img src="https://www.unixtutorial.org/images/chown-user-group-file-1.jpg-1.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-2550" srcset="https://34hkt337byg024dljl2cquwz-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/images/chown-user-group-file-1.jpg-1.jpg 712w, https://34hkt337byg024dljl2cquwz-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/images/chown-user-group-file-1.jpg-1-300x169.jpg 300w" sizes="(max-width: 712px) 100vw, 712px" /><figcaption><strong>chown command</strong></figcaption></figure>



<p><strong><a href="/commands/chown">chown</a></strong> is a <a href="/basic-unix-command">basic Unix command</a>, super useful and very powerful. I have provided a <strong><a href="https://www.unixtutorial.org/chown-example">chown example</a></strong> earlier, but would like to show another common way it's used.</p>



<h2>chown: update ownership recursively</h2>



<p><a href="https://www.unixtutorial.org/chown-example">chown command</a> uses -R option to apply changes recursively.</p>



<p>For example, if I have a <strong>/Users/greys/unixtutorial</strong> directory with the following layout:</p>



<pre class="wp-block-preformatted">file1<br>file2<br>dir1/file3</pre>



<p>&#8230; then it's very easy to show the difference between chown and chown -R commands.</p>



<p>Let's go to the <strong>/Users/greys/unixtutorial</strong> directory:</p>



<pre class="wp-block-preformatted">greys@maverick:~ $ cd /Users/greys/unixtutorial<br>greys@maverick:~/unixtutorial $</pre>



<p>Now, let's look at the files with the <strong><a href="/commands/ls">ls command</a></strong>:</p>



<pre class="wp-block-preformatted">greys@maverick:~/unixtutorial $ ls -al *
 -rw-r--r--  1 greys  staff  0  8 Oct 22:55 <strong>file1</strong>
 -rw-r--r--  1 greys  staff  0  8 Oct 22:55 <strong>file2</strong>
<strong>dir1</strong>:
 total 0
 drwxr-xr-x  3 greys  staff   96  8 Oct 22:55 .
 drwxr-xr-x  5 greys  staff  160  8 Oct 22:55 ..
 -rw-r--r--  1 greys  staff    0  8 Oct 22:55 <strong>file3</strong></pre>



<p>Everything belongs to my own user, <strong>greys</strong> and my primary group: <strong>staff</strong>.</p>



<p>Time to change ownership of everything in the current directory:</p>



<pre class="wp-block-preformatted">greys@maverick:~/unixtutorial $ <strong>sudo chown root:wheel *</strong></pre>



<p>Checking files with <strong><a href="/commands/ls">ls </a></strong>again, I can see that immediate contents of the /Users/greys/unixtutorial directory (where I was at the time of running chown) got updated ownership: file1 and file2, along with dir1, now belong to root:wheel. </p>



<p>But <strong>file3</strong> was in a <strong>dir1</strong> subdirectory, so it stayed intact and still belongs to greys:staff:</p>



<pre class="wp-block-preformatted">greys@maverick:~/unixtutorial $ ls -al *

-rw-r--r--  1 root  wheel  0  8 Oct 22:55 file1

-rw-r--r--  1 root  wheel  0  8 Oct 22:55 file2
dir1:
 total 0
 drwxr-xr-x  3 root   wheel   96  8 Oct 22:55 .
 drwxr-xr-x  5 root   wheel  160  8 Oct 22:55 ..
 -<strong>rw-r--r--  1 greys  staff    0  8 Oct 22:55 file3</strong></pre>



<p>That's because without the -R (recursive) option, <strong><a href="/commands/chown">chown</a></strong> will only inspect and update files in the current directory, but not in any of its subdirectories (or their subdirectories, and so on).</p>



<p>Running the same command with -R option does the trick:</p>



<pre class="wp-block-preformatted">greys@maverick:~/unixtutorial $ <strong>sudo chown -R root:wheel *</strong>
greys@maverick:~/unixtutorial $ ls -al *
-rw-r--r--  1 root  wheel  0  8 Oct 22:55 file1
-rw-r--r--  1 root  wheel  0  8 Oct 22:55 file2
dir1:
total 0
drwxr-xr-x  3 root  wheel   96  8 Oct 22:55 .
drwxr-xr-x  5 root  wheel  160  8 Oct 22:55 ..
<strong>-rw-r--r--  1 root  wheel    0  8 Oct 22:55 file3</strong></pre>



<p>Hope you learned something new, come back for more!</p>



<h2>See Also</h2>



